	<li id="comment-83423">
		<img alt='' src='http://0.gravatar.com/avatar/01b8aad10323f3a55484e05d2adf7d67?s=44&#038;d=http%3A%2F%2F0.gravatar.com%2Favatar%2Fad516503a11cd5ca435acc9bb6523536%3Fs%3D44' class='avatar avatar-44' height='44' width='44' />		<p>
			<p>No, I am not underestimating the scale of HFTs. My points are</p>
<p>Completely Independent Prop HFT should abide by Reg T fully and preemptively. And the Reg T applies to even unexecuted open orders. The capital cost is quite high. Layering short orders are practically impossible as all the short orders should have borrowed the stocks in advance. Don&#8217;t tell me HFT can borrow stocks in milliseconds.</p>
<p>Most HFTs are working as a broker dealer or just using BD&#8217;s regulatory exemption. To utilize the BD&#8217;s exemption, the regulatory checks should be done through firm wide regulatory checking system. There is no room for optimization.</p>
<p>Once, a BDs&#8217; exemption is utilized, the system is a BD. As such, the system should 1) maintain orderly and fair market and 2) keep its fiduciary obligation. It does not matter TD America routed the order to the system or not. Once the system sees an order (X) that is not its own, the system should stop any processing its own order till the order X is published by the exchange if the order is routed to an exchange.</p>
