			<p>If poker were legal, would the FTC allow a poker site that lets one person see another person&#8217;s hand before they bet? Of course not, because it&#8217;s not fair to everyone involved.<br />
Would anyone play on that poker site? Of course not, because it&#8217;s playing with a bunch of cheaters.<br />
When that game is your whole economy and the financial well being and confidence of your citizens, it&#8217;s up to the government to weed out the cheaters especially if it&#8217;s out in the open and affecting consumer confidence.<br />
Do you know people that would like to play in a poker game where you can see the other person&#8217;s cards? Absolutely! It&#8217;s not honest but there are people ready and eager to steal from the unsuspecting. So that would drive normal investors to seek out these types of advantages because they realize they have been on the short end of the stick and want to change teams.  When this happens it will exacerbate the situation and lead to a future of all cheaters who are no longer playing poker and the market will die.<br />
If cheaters go unchecked they get greedier and greedier because they don&#8217;t really think they are cheating and nobody is calling them on it. </p>
<p>This boils down to the importance of consumer confidence for our US economy.<br />
Peace!<br />
